Object Detection Challange¶

Goal: Build a solution for child seat localization in the passanger vehicle.

Dataset: The dataset used for this project is a made of synthetic data and it can be found here.

Problem: Detect child seat in the passanger vehicle.

  • Download and prepare dataset
  • Exploratory Data Analysis
  • Related word academic/industry
  • Model arquitecture
  • Enhance data
  • Write credits at the end

gpus = tensorflow.config.list_physical_devices('GPU')
if gpus:
  try:
    # Currently, memory growth needs to be the same across GPUs
    for gpu in gpus:
      tensorflow.config.experimental.set_memory_growth(gpu, True)
    logical_gpus = tensorflow.config.list_logical_devices('GPU')
    print(len(gpus), "Physical GPUs,", len(logical_gpus), "Logical GPUs")
  except RuntimeError as e:
    # Memory growth must be set before GPUs have been initialized
    print(e)

def make_dataset(path: str, type='train', output_path='/content/data'):
  coco = Coco()

  for i in LABEL_MAP.keys():
    coco.add_category(CocoCategory(id=int(i), name=LABEL_MAP[i]))

  for car_model in car_models:
    folder_path = os.path.join(path, car_model, type, 'RGB_wholeImage')

    for file in os.listdir(folder_path)[:1000]:
      if '.png' in file:
        if '0_0_0' in file:
          continue

        filename = os.path.join(folder_path, file)
        annotation_path = filename.replace('images', 'annotations').replace('RGB_wholeImage', 'boundingBoxes_wholeImage').replace('.png', '.txt')

        # if annotation file is missing skip
        if not os.path.isfile(annotation_path):
          continue


        img = Image.open(filename)
        w, h = img.size

        # save image resized and normalized
        img = img.resize(IMAGE_SHAPE)
        # img = numpy.array(img)/255.0

        # copy image to data folder
        img.convert('RGB').save(os.path.join(output_path, type, file.replace('.png', '.jpeg')))
    
        w_ratio = w/img.size[0]
        h_ratio = h/img.size[1]

        coco_image = CocoImage(
            file_name=file.replace('.png', '.jpeg'), 
            height=IMAGE_SHAPE[0], 
            width=IMAGE_SHAPE[1]
            )

        with open(annotation_path, 'r') as f:
          bboxes = f.readlines()

          for box in bboxes:
            box = box.replace('\n', '').split(',')

            class_type, xmin, ymin, xmax, ymax = box

            xmin = int(int(xmin)/w_ratio)
            ymin = int(int(ymin)/h_ratio)
            xmax = int(int(xmax)/w_ratio)
            ymax = int(int(ymax)/h_ratio)


            width = xmax - xmin
            height = ymax - ymin

            coco_image.add_annotation(
                    CocoAnnotation(
                        bbox=[xmin, ymin, width, height],
                        category_id=int(class_type),
                        category_name=LABEL_MAP[class_type])
                    )

          coco.add_image(coco_image)

  return coco

def pbtxt_from_classlist(l, pbtxt_path):

   pbtxt_text = ''
   print(l)

   for i, c in enumerate(l):
      pbtxt_text += 'item {\n    id: ' + str(i + 1) + '\n    display_name: "' + str(c) + '"\n}\n\n'

   with open(pbtxt_path, "w+") as pbtxt_file:
      pbtxt_file.write(pbtxt_text)

Related Word¶

As shown in the benchmark available here, the team from sviro got the following results for one model of car only (BMW x5):

  • mAP: 0.349
  • mAP 50: 0.653
  • mAP 75: 0.314

The above metrics will be the baseline for our model selection.

Model¶

For this problem I chose the model Efficientdet (arxiv). This model is said to achieve state-of-the-art 55.1mAP on COCO test-dev using fewer parammeters than other SOTA algorithms. Many versions of this models is available for finetunning as it is a good model for transfer learning. The EfficientDet model uses as backbone the EfficientNet architecture that is made to obtain better accuracy and efficiency.

For this project I will be using EfficientDet-D3, a 12.0M params model that achieved 47.5 mAP on COCO dataset.

Train model¶

Data Augmentation

Data augmentation is a very important step when training a deep neural network model as it helps the model generalize better and avoid overfitting to the data. For this project I chose only to do horizontal flipping. This function flips the image horizontaly, for example, if we have a 1_0_4 class we would get a 4_0_1 class after this process.

    means `tf.py_function`s can use accelerators such as GPUs as well as

    (it is not differentiable, and manipulates numpy arrays). It drops the
    stateful argument making all functions stateful.

In [ ]:
def run_detection(image_path: str):
  image_test = Image.open(image_path)
  image_test = image_test.resize(IMAGE_SHAPE)
  image_test = numpy.array(image_test)
  input_tensor = tensorflow.convert_to_tensor(image_test)
  input_tensor = input_tensor[tensorflow.newaxis, ...]

  detections = detect_fn(input_tensor)
  detections = {key:value.numpy() for key,value in detections.items()}
  image_np_with_detections = image_test.copy()
  viz_utils.visualize_boxes_and_labels_on_image_array(
      image_np_with_detections,
      detections['detection_boxes'][0],
      (detections['detection_classes'][0] + 0).astype(int),
      detections['detection_scores'][0],
      category_index,
      use_normalized_coordinates=True,
      min_score_thresh=.2,
      agnostic_mode=False,
  )
  pyplot.figure(figsize=(5,5), dpi=200)
  pyplot.axis("off")
  pyplot.imshow(image_np_with_detections)
  pyplot.show()

Next Steps¶

In a short time we were able to train a detection model to detect object/persons in the backseat of 2 different car models, BMW i3 and Tesla Model3, with an accuracy close to the ones found by the SVIRO team. More time is needed to investigate the best approach to train this model, such as:

  • Train 1 model for each car and compare the results with a single model for every car model.
  • Train model on the full dataset for each car model.
  • Train model with a higher number of steps.
  • Apply other data augmentation techniques such as, rotations, color distortion and image occlusion.
  • Train model with a bigger BATCH_SIZE.
